For new miners, validators, and bystanders, let me first explain how our subnet operate, we solve NP-hard problems. In particular, Graph problems that are NP-hard currently. What is the best solver to solve graph problems? There really isn't one. Some have a general edge over the others, but there will always be problems where another solver have an "accidental" algorithmic edge.  This is where Bittensor comes in for our problem, and is important for us, we need solvers that are diversed, solvers that can generally solve well and climb to the top of our incentive curves, and solvers that does not perform as well but covers the edge cases of these general good solvers. This second set of solvers may never climb to the top of the incentive curve, but they are important to us. Together, they form the Pareto front for our subnet's solution. This is the reason why we can beat SOTA models, this is the reason why we can beat commercial solutions. 

Now, would the miners of the second set of solution ever earn much? Probably not. How much registration cost can they afford? Probably not much either. Meanwhile, top miners, rich OG miners of our subnet will always have the ability to burn and register.

Leaving the max_reg_cost to the system = allowing set 1 miners to always prop the reg costs up, creating a barrier for set 2 miners.

We need both set 1 and set 2 miners for our product to work, and we know set 2 miners doesn't earn much with the current reward mechanism. messages.content: I don't see the difference between RCMDMTSP and CVRP. Could you enlighten me?

In a standard/common CVRP (note that there can be a few variations), you're given:
- A single depot
-  set of customers, each with a known demand
- A fleet of identical vehicles, each with a capacity limit
- A distance (or cost) matrix between all locations (depot and customers)

Goal:
- Find the set of routes for all vehicles such that:
- Each customer is visited exactly once
- The total demand on each route does not exceed vehicle capacity
- All routes start and end at the depot
- The total cost (e.g., distance or time) is minimized

How does this differ from RCMDMTSP? Our problem RCMDMTSP is actually more adapted to the real world. 
- Multiple depots ==> A company will usually have more than 1 warehouse
- Different capacity vehicles instead of multiple identical ones (ie all vehicles have the same capacity) ==> A company will usually own delivery vehicles of different sizes to meet different demands.
- Much more complex to solve optimally due to the 2 factors above than CVRP
I hope this answers your question @Decent
